DIV4.P:
Talbot, to the King and Princes, upon an arraign∣ment of Sir John Fastolfe This is not our quondam merry Knight, though the near resem∣blance of the names, and pusillanimity of the characters, might possibly render the person equivocal to the reader., Knight of the Garter, for cowardice:

When first this Order was ordained, my lords,

Knights of the Garter were of noble birth;

Valiant and virtuous, full of haughty courage;

Such as were grown to credit by the wars;

Not fearing death, nor shrinking for distress,

But always resolute in most extremes.

He then that is not furnished in this sort,

Doth but usurp the sacred name of Knight,

Prophaning this most honourable Order;

And should, if I were worthy to be judge,

Be quite degraded, like a hedge-born swain,

That doth presume to boast of gentle blood.

DIV5.P:
Here the good duke, upon the occasion of his wife's ignominy and penance, makes a reflection on the general nature of human life, which he illustrates with an apt allusion:

Gloucester.

Thus sometimes hath the brightest day a cloud;

And after summer evermore succeeds

The barren winter, with his nipping cold;

So cares and joys abound, as seasons fleet.

The above scene closes, very properly, with a truly Christian sentiment, by the King, who is, all through, represented by Shakespeare as a religious▪ moral, domestic, easy-tempered man;
Famed for mildness, peace, and prayer Third Part.:
Just such a prince, whose very goodness, for want of sense and spirit, must ever render the dupe of Mi∣nisters, and the sport of Faction.

DIV4.P:
Sweet are the slumbers of the virtuous man, says Addison, in his Cato; and a modern writer, in a poem on the subject of dreams, most emphatically expresses himself thus:
Nor are the oppressor's crimes in sleep forgot;
He starts appalled, for conscience slumbers not Something New, Chap. XLIX..

DIV5.P:
In the same Scene, when Lear requires his three daughters to declare the several portions of their love and respect towards him, the eldest addresses herself to him thus:

Goneril.

Sir,

I love you more than words can wield the matter,


Dearer than eye-sight, space, and liberty;

Beyond what can be valued, rich or rare;

No less than life, with grace, health, beauty, honour;

As much as child e'er loved, or father found;

A love that makes breath poor, and speech unable,

Beyond all manner of so much I love you.

To which he replies, very justly,

Wisdom and goodness to the vile seem vile;

Filths savour but themselves. . . . . .

The noble Timon, being rendered uneasy at the too servile deferences paid him by his clients, justly says,

Nay, ceremony was but devised, at first,

To set a gloss on faint deeds, hollow welcomes;


Recanting goodness, sorry ere 'tis shewn;

But where there is true friendship, there needs none.

To which Timon replies, with a competent know∣ledge of human nature; for he seems to be inspired here, as before See the last passage of Scene II. of the former Act, with the remark upon it.:

These old fellows

Have their ingratitude in them hereditary By hereditary he means naturally, or connate with old age.;

Their blood is caked, is cold, it seldom flows;

'Tis lack of friendly warmth they are not kind;

And nature, as it grows again tow'rd earth,

Is fashioned for the journey, dull and heavy.

To which the more experienced steward replies to himself,

Would I could not! That thought is bounty's foe;

Being free itself, it thinks all others so.

Alcibiades, pleading before the Senate, for the life of a friend who had killed his antagonist in


a fair rencounter, thus addresses himself to the court:

Health, honour, and compassion to the Senate!

I am an humble suitor to your virtues;

For pity is the virtue of the law;

And none but tyrants use it cruelly.

Lady Macbeth, speaking here of Duncan's grooms, says,

That which hath made them drunk, hath made me bold;

What hath quenched them, hath given me fire.

To which Ulysses, further on in the same Scene, adds,

They tax our policy, and call it cowardice;

Count wisdom as no member of the war;

Forestall our prescience, and esteem no act

But that of hand—The still and mental parts,

That do contrive how many hands shall strike,

When fitness calls them on, and know the measure,

By their observant toil, of th' enemy's weight;

Why this hath not a finger's dignity;

They call this bed-work, mappery, closet-war—

So that the ram, that batters down the wall,

For the great swing and rudeness of its poize,

They place before his hand that made the engine;

Or those, that with the fierceness of their souls,

By reason guide its execution.

There is something very affecting in the self-ex∣postulation entered into by Hamlet, in this place,


just before he proceeds to hold the conference with his mother:

Soft; now to my mother—

O heart, lose not thy nature; let not ever

The soul of Nero enter this firm bosom;

Let me be cruel Cruel, for sever., but not unnatural;

I will speak daggers to her, but use none.

My tongue and soul in this be hypocrites;

How in my words soever she be shent Shent, sentenced, or condemned.,

To give them seals To give them warrant or authority to execute justice., never my soul consent!
